Looked into this. Looks like some internal problem with interop server; it failed to resolve the metadata to be sent for some unknown reason when responding to method `/grpc.testing.TestService/EmptyCall
`. Got a debug that caught where it happened:
```
Process 59130 launched: '../../../bins/dbg/interop_server' (x86_64)
I0202 17:16:36.623577000 140736153174976 server_builder.cc:247] Synchronous server. Num CQs: 1, Min pollers: 1, Max Pollers: 2147483647, CQ timeout (msec): 1000
E0202 17:16:39.483448000 123145420587008 call.c:807] validate_metadata: {"created":"@1486084599.483423000","description":"Illegal header value","file":"src/core/lib/surface/validate_metadata.c","file_line":55,"offset":65,"raw_bytes":"46 6f 6f 20 67 72 70 63 2d 6f 62 6a 63 2f 31 2e 30 2e 32 20 67 72 70 63 2d 63 2f 33 2e 30 2e 30 2d 64 65 76 20 28 69 6f 73 3b 20 63 68 74 74 70 32 3b 20 67 72 65 65 6e 29 31 30 30 30 38 62 33 40 17 0d 'Foo grpc-objc/1.0.2 grpc-c/3.0.0-dev (ios; chttp2; green)10008b3@..'"}
```
The code location:
```
additional_metadata_count=0) + 335 at call.c:808
   805 	               !GRPC_LOG_IF_ERROR(
   806 	                   "validate_metadata",

-> 808 	      break;
   809 	    }
   810 	    l->md = grpc_mdelem_from_grpc_metadata(exec_ctx, (grpc_metadata *)md);
   811 	  }
```

The C++ interop server seems to be trying to send an invalid (and
nonsensical) metadata entry "Foo grpc-objc/1.0.2 grpc-c/3.0.0-dev (ios;
chttp2; green)10008b3@.." which not only does not correspond to a C++
server, but also contains invalid bytes at the end (reason why the
validation call failed). It smells like memory corruption in the interop
server. Running it under asan will probably help.
